\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec3 AI is reaching a point where everyone can have a personal super-assistant that helps them learn and do almost anything. Who gets access to that level of intelligence will shape whether AI expands opportunity or reinforces the same divides.\cb1 \
\cb2 We\'92ve been working to make powerful AI accessible to everyone through our free product and low-cost subscription tier, ChatGPT Go, which has launched in 171 countries since August. Today we\'92re\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://openai.com/index/introducing-chatgpt-go/"}}{\fldrslt \ul bringing Go to the U.S. and everywhere ChatGPT is available\uc0\u8288 }}, giving people expanded access to messaging, image creation, file uploads and memory for $8 USD/month. In the coming weeks, we\'92re also planning to start testing ads in the U.S. for the free and Go tiers, so more people can benefit from our tools with fewer usage limits or without having to pay. Plus, Pro, Business, and Enterprise subscriptions will not include ads.\cb1 \
\cb2 People trust ChatGPT for many important and personal tasks, so as we introduce ads, it\'92s crucial we preserve what makes ChatGPT valuable in the first place. That means you need to trust that ChatGPT\'92s responses are driven by what\'92s objectively useful, never by advertising. You need to know that your data and conversations are protected and never sold to advertisers. And we need to keep a high bar and give you control over your experience so you see truly relevant, high-quality ads\'97and can turn off personalization if you want.\cb1 \
\cb2 Given that, we want to be clear about the principles that guide our approach to advertising:\cb1 \
